node.text:
Forward Shoulders⤵️
Follow 👉@backpainguide for daily pain relief tips! 📚

❤️Tag a friend in the comments who needs this!
.
Today we’re discussing a controversial one - the rounded or forward shoulder. First off, before we tackle this, We have a top notch YouTube video covering the face pull, breaking down how to do it, how to customize it by your goals, and how to get more out of it if you’re using bands. So check that out.
.
Now let’s talk about shoulders. This is one where there is a lot of misinformation. If you search about forward shoulders online, you’ll be drowned by information about the dangers of them and how they’re the cause for neck pain, shoulder pain, back pain, and more. While well intentioned, it’s based on dated information.
.
When you first read about this, it can be hard. You have probably had neck, shoulder, or back pain, worked on “changing” your forward shoulders and found relief. I’m not arguing that didn’t happen. However, why your pain changed is a lot more complicated than just a change in shoulder posture or position.
.
The exercises shown here (and the face pull YouTube video) aim to strengthen the upper back. The provides benefit in increasing the capacity of these muscles to 1. Manage load on themselves better and 2. Provide more options for movement at adjacent regions, taking stress off others.
.
So to wrap up, forward shoulders aren’t inherently bad, you don’t have to try to change them, you may find benefit from altering their position temporarily, you may also find benefit strengthening it, being more active, and much more. Focusing in specifically on the rounded shoulders isn’t necessary, and may be negative in the long run.
.
🎊These are not secret drills or techniques, just some options to help inspire people to move more and live a higher quality life.
❗️This is not medical advice

Do you have neck pain?
Follow 👉@easypainrelief for daily pain relief tips! 📚

📢Find this helpful? Share it with your friends!
🔔Turn on post notifications so you never miss a post!

These neck stretches could be the ones for you!
.
There are 3 major muscles in the neck that tend to create pain for a lot of people.
.
Those are the upper trapezius, the levator scapulae and the scalenes.
.
The upper traps and levator connect the shoulder blade to the neck, while the scalenes connect from the ribs to the neck.
.
Each one of these stretches specifically targets one of those muscles to give you the nest possible stretch all the way around the neck.
.
Do each of these on both sides, holding for 20 seconds each.

node.text:
💥Rounded Shoulders💥
Follow 👉@dr.backpain for daily pain management tips📚
-
❤️ TAG or SHARE this post with someone who needs to see this!
-
😱 "Rounded shoulders" posture gets a lot of bad press on the internet, and it's usually explained very poorly
-
🔍 Search "Rounded Shoulders" on Google and you'll spend all day scrolling through "Fixes", "Posture Corrections", and endless before and after ✅❌ "comparison" photos
-
💯 But here's the deal: Specific postural positions DO NOT DIRECTLY "cause" pain. Nothing DIRECTLY "causes" pain, because pain is COMPLEX and there are ALWAYS multiple factors that influence pain in any ONE person at any ONE time
-
🚨 However, staying in ONE position for LONG PERIODS CAN CONTRIBUTE to pain, regardless of the position (even standing/sitting straight up in "perfect" posture!)
-
🤔 But because so many people in today's society tend to spend LONG TIMES in a "ROUNDED SHOULDERS" position, hunched over the computer for hours and hours without moving much (if at all), this position has become demonized as a "cause" of dysfunction
-
🧐 Let's rethink that...
-
⁉️ What if it's okay to hang out in this position, but instead of staying here for hours, we move a bit more throughout the day?
-
🤸🏻 Stretch, stand up, walk, move into directions we haven't been moving into as much recently
-
⁉️ Did we "fix" anything?
-
🤔 Or are we just giving the body more of what it wants? MOVEMENT.
-
🤓 I could go deeper into this, but this is Instagram and I'm limited to 2200 characters...and I know you guys like exercises 🤷🏻♂️
-
⬆️ So reflect on what I said above, then use these exercises to move into positions and strengthen muscles that you MAY be neglecting in your everyday routine
-
🙏🏼 But please, for the love of God, don't ask me how to "fix" your rounded shoulders for good 😖
-
❌ That's an outdated narrative that needs to die and lay to rest in the rehab graveyard ☠️
-
Follow 👉@dr.backpain for daily pain management advice📚

“SHOULDER IMPINGEMENT” REHAB
—
Subacromial/shoulder impingement is a diagnosis often given to individuals experiencing pain in the front and/or side of their shoulder.
—
However, the diagnosis is being utilized less and less because impingement of structures in the subacromial space likely isn’t the culprit for symptoms. Therefore, subacromial pain syndrome (SAPS) is favored by many researchers and clinicians at this time. Other names have been suggested as well such as Rotator Cuff Related Shoulder Pain or simply just shoulder pain.
—
The great thing about this is that most people respond very favorably to exercise as we see that conservative management can be just as effective as surgery.
—
For individuals with highly irritable symptoms, incorporating more “pulling” exercises than “pushing” exercises can be beneficial. You might have to take a break from certain exercises like bench pressing or overhead pressing if they’re aggravating, but you want to continue training in some capacity rather than completely resting.
—
The exercises demonstrated can be helpful to increase range of motion and strengthen muscles surrounding the shoulder and back.
—
If you are interested in learning more, check out our shoulder impingement program (currently on sale: use MD30 for 30% OFF)

How often do you train your rotator cuff?
Follow 👉@easypainrelief for daily pain relief tips! 📚

I recently got the following question: Why do you do so many “accessory” exercise? — to which I replied: because I didn’t do enough in the past causing all sorts of problems, namely lack of progress, injuries, and poor movement mechanics.

I might be sounding like a broken record at this point recommending so many exercises that target the little muscles surrounding the shoulder joint & the scapula thoracic joint. However, I feel called to share this with all of you so you avoid all the mistakes I’ve made during my training history.

Compound exercises are key to progress and should be the bulk of our training. However, it is absolutely essential that we start strengthening the shoulder & the scapula stabilizer muscles as early as possible. This in turn will make all your “main exercises” that much effective and safer.

Here are a few exercises that will improve your upper body strength and stability in ways I cannot even begin to explain, especially any movement that’s overhead. If your goals are planche, front lever, handstand, HSPU, or any Bodyweight skill for that matter, these are a MUST. Even if you only want to get stronger at pull ups, these are still crucial to allow the mechanics of your body work effectively, and safely.

We simply don’t do enough of “the little things” thinking they are a waste of time. They are not. I recommend you start now. You’ll be glad you did =]

I won’t go into detail of each exercise on this post. All of them serve different purposes, but all of them have a lot of similarities. The angle, the speed, the position of your arms, all will target these muscles in a different way.

I recommend not to get overwhelm with all of them. Pick 2 and add them to the end of your upper body workouts for a few weeks and see how your body respond. Begin experimenting with others and find what works best for your own unique body.

That’s all for this post =] just a little reminder and a few options to try.

💫 Back Pain - Core Stability
Follow 👉@dr.backpain for daily pain relief tips! 📚

🔹 Low back pain effects nearly everyone in at least some point of life. It is hard to even imagine how much we use our low back until an injury occurs. If you are recovering from a low back injury, it is important to take it slow and have a skilled professional guide you through the rehabilitation process.

🔸 Initially, decreasing pain and normalizing mobility will be of utmost importance. This can possibly takes multiple weeks. After, a progressive strengthening and core stabilization program will set the foundation for returning back to doing the things you love to do.

🔹 Often, patients will stop physical therapy when pain abolishes because they feel “healed.” But this can be deceiving and the final stages of rehab very well could be the most important. That is restoring functional mobility and strength that will complete a 100% full recovery and bulletproof your spine from further injury.

👆 SEE ABOVE and 👉 SWIPE LEFT to view some great mid to later stage low back rehab options to improve core stability.

💥3 Minute Posture Routine💥
Follow 👉@treatingbackpain for daily pain management advice📚

Rounded shoulders and Forward head posture are a common thing. We all have to fight against gravity every day. On top of that we also have to fight the natural tendency to always be looking down at our phones! 📱👀

How many of you just realized you were looking down at your phone? 🙋‍♂️ 😂

If your shoulders are rounding and your head is forward that doesn’t guarantee you will have pain BUT 🍑 we know that staying in ANY posture or position for too long is not good for us and can cause irritation. Our bodies like to MOVE!

It’s important to frequently move and work into the opposite directions that gravity tends to pull us into.

Also, who doesn’t want to look taller and more confident? Am I right? When it comes to height I need all the help I can get! 😂

Here’s a 3 min routine you can do so that those shoulders and chin don’t dump forward and you can keep every inch your mom and dad gave you! All you need is a stick! 🧹

Hope this helps! Give gravity the middle finger and stay tall my friends! 💪
